body:
If there are two trait methods of the same name and different parameters and only one is implemented for a type but the user tries to call the other (using different parameters) rustc complains about number/type of parameters without any hint of possible different problem.

Given the following code: [playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=6c184630c6f07812c1582cd9c8733fac)

```rust
trait Foo {
    fn do_stuff(&self);
}

trait Bar {
    fn do_stuff(&self, bar: bool);
}

impl Bar for u32 {
    fn do_stuff(&self, bar: bool) {
        println!("Bar: {}, {}", self, bar);
    }
}

fn main() {
    42_u32.do_stuff();
}
```

The current output is:

```
error[E0061]: this function takes 1 argument but 0 arguments were supplied
  --> src/main.rs:16:12
   |
16 |     42_u32.do_stuff();
   |            ^^^^^^^^- supplied 0 arguments
   |            |
   |            expected 1 argument
   |
note: associated function defined here
  --> src/main.rs:6:8
   |
6  |     fn do_stuff(&self, bar: bool);
   |        ^^^^^^^^

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0061`.
```

<!-- The following is not always necessary. -->
Ideally the output should look like:

```
error[E0061]: this function takes 1 argument but 0 arguments were supplied
  --> src/main.rs:16:12
   |
16 |     42_u32.do_stuff();
   |            ^^^^^^^^- supplied 0 arguments
   |            |
   |            expected 1 argument
   |
note: you may be attempting to call `do_stuff` method of trait `Foo` which is not implemented for `u32`
  --> src/main.rs:2:8
   |
2  |     fn do_stuff(&self);
   |        ^^^^^^^^- trait `Foo` not implemented for `u32`
   |
note: associated function defined here
  --> src/main.rs:6:8
   |
6  |     fn do_stuff(&self, bar: bool);
   |        ^^^^^^^^

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0061`.
```

The user may be led to wrong direction by this error message. Presenting both possibilities may be helpful. The traits can come from different modules/crates (real world case: `Hash` from `std` and cryptographic `Hash` trait.)

Note that similar problem happens if number of arguments is the same but the types are different (try adding e.g. `&str` to `Foo` and call it with `"foo"`).

Nightly looks same.
